Chapter 3: Problem Formulation

3.1 Continuous Thermal Dynamics

Let \Omega \subset \mathbb{R}^2 be the spacecraft surface. The temperature field T(x,t) satisfies the nonlinear heat equation:

\rho c_p \frac{\partial T}{\partial t} = \nabla \cdot \big( k(T) \nabla T \big) + q_{\text{aero}}(x,t) - \nabla \cdot q_{\text{cool}}(x,t) - q_{\text{rad}}(x,t)

where

· \rho is the density, c_p the specific heat, and k(T) the thermal conductivity.
· q_{\text{aero}}(x,t) is the aerodynamic + plasma heat flux (external disturbance).
· q_{\text{cool}}(x,t) is the active cooling flux (control input).
· q_{\text{rad}}(x,t) = \epsilon(x,t) \sigma (T^4 - T_{\infty}^4) is the radiative cooling, with \epsilon(x,t) controllable via VEM.

Boundary conditions: insulated edges except for the surface exposed to the flow.

3.2 Discretization as a Networked System

We discretize \Omega into N finite‑volume cells, each associated with an agent i. Let \mathcal{G} = (\mathcal{V},\mathcal{E}) be the communication graph, assumed undirected and connected during nominal operation. The coupling term \nabla \cdot (k \nabla T) is approximated by:

\sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} k_{ij}(T) (T_j - T_i)

where k_{ij}(T) are effective conductances that may depend on the average temperature.

3.3 Agent Dynamics (Second‑Order)

Define the state \mathbf{x}_i = [T_i,\; \dot{T}_i]^\top. Linearizing around a nominal temperature T_{i0} yields:

\dot{\mathbf{x}}_i = \mathbf{A}_i \mathbf{x}_i + \mathbf{B}_i \mathbf{u}_i + \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} \mathbf{L}_{ij} (\mathbf{x}_j - \mathbf{x}_i) + \mathbf{w}_i(t)

where

· \mathbf{A}_i captures local thermal inertia and radiation linearization:
    \mathbf{A}_i = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ -\frac{k_{ii}}{\rho c_p V_i} & -\frac{1}{\rho c_p V_i} \frac{\partial k}{\partial T} \dot{T}_i \end{bmatrix} (simplified).
· \mathbf{B}_i \in \mathbb{R}^{2 \times 3} maps control inputs \mathbf{u}_i = [u_i^{(1)}, u_i^{(2)}, u_i^{(3)}]^\top (transpiration flow, microchannel flow, emissivity) to state derivatives.
· \mathbf{L}_{ij} are constant coupling matrices derived from the conductances.
· \mathbf{w}_i(t) lumps the external heat flux and linearization errors.

Actuator constraints: \mathbf{u}_i \in \mathcal{U}_i \subset \mathbb{R}^3, compact convex set.

Safety constraint: T_i(t) \leq T_{\max} for all t, where T_{\max} is the maximum allowable temperature (material limit).

3.4 Control Objective

We seek to minimize the peak temperature:

J = \max_{i,t} T_i(t)

subject to actuator constraints and a global energy budget \sum_i \int_0^{t_f} \|\mathbf{u}_i(t)\|_{\mathbf{R}}^2 dt \leq E_{\text{total}}.

