Chapter 5: Distributed Model Predictive Control

5.1 Local Optimization Problem

At each sampling time t_k, agent i solves:

\begin{aligned}
\min_{\mathbf{u}_i(\cdot)} \quad & J_i = \sum_{\ell=0}^{N-1} \Big( \| \mathbf{x}_i(t_{k+\ell}) - \mathbf{x}_i^{\text{ref}}(t_{k+\ell}) \|_{\mathbf{Q}_i}^2 + \| \mathbf{u}_i(t_{k+\ell}) \|_{\mathbf{R}_i}^2 \Big) \\
&\quad + \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} \| \mathbf{x}_i(t_{k+N}) - \hat{\mathbf{x}}_j(t_{k+N}) \|_{\mathbf{S}_{ij}}^2
\end{aligned}

subject to:

· Discrete‑time dynamics: \mathbf{x}_i(t_{k+\ell+1}) = \mathbf{f}_i(\mathbf{x}_i(t_{k+\ell}), \mathbf{u}_i(t_{k+\ell}), \mathbf{x}_{\mathcal{N}_i}(t_{k+\ell})).
· Constraints: \mathbf{u}_i(t_{k+\ell}) \in \mathcal{U}_i, T_i(t_{k+\ell}) \leq T_{\max}.
· Terminal cost: penalizes disagreement with neighbors (using predicted trajectories \hat{\mathbf{x}}_j from previous iterations).

5.2 Accelerated ADMM for Real‑Time Implementation

We rewrite the coupled problem as a global optimization with consensus constraints \mathbf{x}_i = \mathbf{z}_{ij} for each edge. The augmented Lagrangian is:

\mathcal{L}_\rho(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{z},\lambda) = \sum_i J_i(\mathbf{x}_i) + \sum_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{E}} \lambda_{ij}^\top (\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{z}_{ij}) + \frac{\rho}{2} \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{z}_{ij}\|^2 + \frac{\rho}{2} \|\mathbf{x}_j - \mathbf{z}_{ij}\|^2

We apply Nesterov‑accelerated ADMM (fast ADMM) to achieve O(1/k^2) convergence. The updates are:

\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{x}_i^{k+1} &= \arg\min_{\mathbf{x}_i} \left( J_i(\mathbf{x}_i) + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} (\lambda_{ij}^k)^\top \mathbf{x}_i + \frac{\rho}{2} \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{z}_{ij}^k\|^2 \right) \\
\mathbf{z}_{ij}^{k+1} &= \frac{\mathbf{x}_i^{k+1} + \mathbf{x}_j^{k+1}}{2} + \frac{\lambda_{ij}^k}{2\rho} \\
\lambda_{ij}^{k+1} &= \lambda_{ij}^k + \rho (\mathbf{x}_i^{k+1} - \mathbf{z}_{ij}^{k+1})
\end{aligned}

with momentum terms added to accelerate primal updates.

Proposition 1 (Convergence Rate).
If each J_i is strongly convex with modulus \mu and has Lipschitz gradient with constant L, then the accelerated ADMM iterates satisfy:

\|\mathbf{u}^k - \mathbf{u}^*\|^2 \leq \frac{C}{k^2}

for some constant C > 0, where \mathbf{u}^* is the optimal solution.

Proof sketch: This follows from standard results on Nesterov acceleration for convex composite optimization. The augmented Lagrangian is strongly convex in \mathbf{x} and the consensus constraints are linear; the momentum term yields the improved rate. See [Nesterov, 2004; Goldstein et al., 2014] for details.

5.3 Event‑Triggered Communication

To reduce communication load and mitigate plasma blackout, each agent broadcasts its state only when the local error exceeds a threshold:

\|\mathbf{x}_i(t) - \mathbf{x}_i(t_{\text{last}})\| \geq \delta_i

where \delta_i > 0 is a design parameter. Neighbors maintain a hold‑state \hat{\mathbf{x}}_j until a new broadcast arrives.

Theorem 1 (Minimum Inter‑Event Time).
Under the event‑triggering condition and assuming \|\dot{\mathbf{x}}_i(t)\| \leq M_i for all t (due to bounded actuators and dynamics), the inter‑event times satisfy \tau_i \geq \delta_i / M_i > 0. Hence, Zeno behavior (infinitely many events in finite time) is excluded.

Proof: Between events, \|\mathbf{x}_i(t) - \mathbf{x}_i(t_{\text{last}})\| \leq \int_{t_{\text{last}}}^t \|\dot{\mathbf{x}}_i(s)\| ds \leq M_i (t - t_{\text{last}}). The next event occurs when this equals \delta_i, giving the lower bound.

