Chapter 6: Stability and Performance Guarantees

6.1 Input‑to‑State Stability (ISS)

Assumption 1 (Local ISS).
For each agent i, with the terminal control law \mathbf{u}_i = \kappa_i(\mathbf{x}_i) (the local DMPC policy when the terminal region is reached), the subsystem \dot{\mathbf{x}}_i = \mathbf{f}_i(\mathbf{x}_i, \kappa_i(\mathbf{x}_i), \mathbf{d}_i) is ISS with respect to the interconnection signal \mathbf{d}_i = \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} \mathbf{L}_{ij} (\mathbf{x}_j - \mathbf{x}_i) + \mathbf{w}_i(t). There exist an ISS Lyapunov function V_i(\mathbf{x}_i) and gains \gamma_{ij} \in \mathcal{K}_\infty such that:

\dot{V}_i \leq -\alpha_i V_i + \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} \gamma_{ij}(V_j) + \beta_i(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty).

Assumption 2 (Small‑Gain Condition).
The matrix \Gamma with entries \gamma_{ij} (interpreted as positive numbers by considering linear gains near the origin) satisfies \rho(\Gamma) < 1, where \rho is the spectral radius.

Theorem 2 (ISS of the Interconnected System).
Under Assumptions 1 and 2, the closed‑loop system with the DMPC scheme is input‑to‑state stable with respect to the disturbance \mathbf{w}(t) = [\mathbf{w}_1^\top,\dots,\mathbf{w}_N^\top]^\top.

Proof: The DMPC algorithm ensures that the terminal constraint is enforced, so the actual closed‑loop trajectory satisfies the ISS inequality for each agent (with the same V_i) for all t (due to recursive feasibility). Define V = \sum_i \lambda_i V_i where \lambda_i > 0 are chosen such that:

\sum_i \lambda_i \left( -\alpha_i V_i + \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} \gamma_{ij}(V_j) \right) \leq -\delta \sum_i V_i

for some \delta > 0. This is possible because \rho(\Gamma) < 1. Then:

\dot{V} \leq -\delta V + \sum_i \lambda_i \beta_i(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty).

Applying the comparison lemma yields:

V(t) \leq e^{-\delta t} V(0) + \frac{1}{\delta} \sum_i \lambda_i \beta_i(\|\mathbf{w}\|_\infty).

Since V_i are positive definite and radially unbounded, this implies uniform boundedness of all states. The explicit ISS gain is obtained by converting the bound on V to a bound on \|\mathbf{x}\|.

6.2 String Stability

Consider a chain topology (e.g., along the stagnation line). Define the tracking error e_i = T_i - T_{\text{ref},i}. String stability requires that the L_2 norm of the error does not amplify along the chain.

Definition 2. The system is string stable if there exists \gamma < 1 such that:

\|E_{i+1}\|_{L_2} \leq \gamma \|E_i\|_{L_2}

for all i, where \|E_i\|_{L_2} = \left( \int_0^\infty |e_i(t)|^2 dt \right)^{1/2}.

Theorem 3 (String Stability).
Under the DMPC scheme with terminal cost matrices \mathbf{S}_{ij} chosen to enforce a small‑gain condition on the interconnection gains, the closed‑loop system is string stable.

Proof: The dynamics along the chain can be written as:

\dot{e}_i = f_i(e_i, e_{i-1}, e_{i+1}, \mathbf{u}_i, \mathbf{w}_i).

The DMPC terminal cost penalizes \|e_i - e_{i+1}\|, effectively imposing a dissipative coupling. Using the small‑gain theorem for interconnected systems in a cascade, we can show that the L_2 gain from e_i to e_{i+1} is less than 1. This follows from the fact that the ISS gains \gamma_{i,i+1} can be made arbitrarily small by increasing the penalty \mathbf{S}_{ij} in the terminal cost. By choosing them such that \gamma < 1, string stability is guaranteed.

6.3 Finite‑Time Stability

Reentry is a finite‑duration process; we need temperatures to drop below a safe threshold within a fixed time \tau_{\text{safe}} < \tau_{\text{failure}}.

Definition 3. The system is finite‑time stable if there exists a settling time function T(\mathbf{x}_0) < \infty such that for all initial states, \|\mathbf{x}(t)\| \leq \varepsilon for all t \geq T(\mathbf{x}_0).

Theorem 4 (Finite‑Time Convergence to Safe Set).
Let \mathcal{B} = \{\mathbf{x} : T_i \leq T_{\max} \ \forall i\} be the safe set. Under the DMPC policy, there exists a constant \tau_{\text{conv}} > 0 such that for any initial condition \mathbf{x}(0), the trajectory enters \mathcal{B} within \tau_{\text{conv}} seconds, and \tau_{\text{conv}} can be chosen less than the material failure time \tau_{\text{failure}}.

Proof: Consider the Lyapunov function V(\mathbf{x}) = \sum_i \frac{1}{2} \|\mathbf{x}_i\|^2. For states outside \mathcal{B}, the DMPC solution ensures that the control input is active and satisfies:

\dot{V} \leq -\alpha V^\beta

for some \alpha > 0, \beta \in (0,1). This inequality follows from the fact that when T_i > T_{\max}, the DMPC cost penalizes the temperature heavily, so the optimal control will apply maximum cooling, leading to a negative definite derivative with a fractional power. The standard finite‑time stability lemma (Bhat & Bernstein, 2000) then gives:

V(t) \leq \left( V(0)^{1-\beta} - \alpha (1-\beta) t \right)^{\frac{1}{1-\beta}}

until the state enters \mathcal{B}. The time to reach the safe set is:

\tau_{\text{conv}} \leq \frac{V(0)^{1-\beta}}{\alpha(1-\beta)}.

This bound depends on the initial state but is finite. By designing the controller (via the terminal cost and the penalty weights), we can make \alpha sufficiently large so that \tau_{\text{conv}} < \tau_{\text{failure}} for all possible initial states.

