Chapter 8: Thermodynamic Optimality

The second law of thermodynamics states that irreversible processes generate entropy. Minimizing entropy production extends material life and reduces cooling requirements.

The global entropy production rate \dot{S}_{\text{gen}} for the TPS can be derived from the heat equation:

\dot{S}_{\text{gen}} = \int_\Omega \frac{|\nabla T|^2}{T^2} k(T) \, d\Omega + \int_\Omega \frac{q_{\text{aero}} - q_{\text{cool}}}{T} \, d\Omega - \int_\Omega \frac{q_{\text{rad}}}{T} \, d\Omega.

After discretization, we obtain:

\dot{S}_{\text{gen}} = \sum_i \frac{q_{\text{aero},i} - q_{\text{cool},i}}{T_i} - \sum_{i,j} \frac{k_{ij}(T_i - T_j)^2}{T_i T_j} + \sum_i \frac{\epsilon_i \sigma (T_i^4 - T_\infty^4)}{T_i}.

Theorem 7 (Near‑Minimum Entropy Production).
Assume the local cost functions J_i are strongly convex and the entropy production functional \int \dot{S}_{\text{gen}} dt is strictly convex in the temperature field. Then the DMPC policy that minimizes the peak temperature subject to actuator constraints achieves the global minimum of total entropy production among all admissible distributed control policies.

Proof sketch: The entropy production rate is convex in the temperature gradients and in the cooling distribution. The DMPC terminal cost penalizes \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j\|^2, which directly reduces the temperature gradients. Moreover, by minimizing the peak temperature, the controller allocates cooling to the hottest spots, which are also the regions with the largest q_{\text{aero}}/T. A variational argument using the convexity of the entropy functional shows that the optimal control for minimizing entropy production is exactly the one that equalizes T as much as possible, which is the objective of the DMPC consensus term. The DMPC solution satisfies the necessary optimality conditions for the entropy minimization problem, and by strict convexity, it is the unique global minimizer.

