Chapter 9: Implementation Architecture

9.1 Physical Tiles

Each tile is additively manufactured from porous silicon carbide (SiC) with embedded channels for transpiration and microcooling. The outer surface is coated with a thermochromic VEM (VO₂). Sensors are embedded near the outer surface and at the bond line.

9.2 Embedded Electronics

Each tile contains:

· Microcontroller: Vorago VA41620 (radiation‑hardened ARM Cortex‑M4, 80 MHz, 1 MB SRAM, 16 MB flash). This device is qualified for space applications with >300 krad TID and SEL immunity.
· Communication: CAN bus interface (redundant twisted pair) and optional UHF wireless for redundancy.
· Power management: DC‑DC converter (28 V input, 3.3 V logic), supercapacitor backup for short‑term power loss.
· Actuator drivers: PWM for transpiration valves, H‑bridge for microchannel pump.

9.3 Supervisor

The supervisor runs on a dual‑redundant RAD750 computer (radiation‑hardened PowerPC) with 256 MB ECC RAM, 2 GB flash. It communicates with the tiles via the CAN bus.

9.4 Fault Tolerance

· Tile failure: Neighbors detect loss of communication and treat the tile as a virtual node with constant state (estimated from last known value and thermal model). The supervisor redistributes cooling budgets.
· Actuator failure: The local controller detects saturation or fault and re‑optimizes with degraded capability; the supervisor may reduce the energy budget for that tile.
· Power loss: Supercapacitor provides power for a few seconds to execute a safe shutdown sequence.

9.5 Software Architecture

The DMPC algorithm is implemented in C with a real‑time operating system (RTEMS). The control task runs at 10 Hz. The ADMM iterations are limited to 10 per sampling interval, using warm‑start from previous solution.



