Appendix A: Mathematical Preliminaries

This appendix collects the definitions, lemmas, and background results used throughout the thesis.

A.1 Notation

Symbol Description
\mathbb{R}^n n-dimensional Euclidean space
\|\cdot\| Euclidean norm (unless specified otherwise)
\|\cdot\|_\infty Essential supremum norm for signals
\mathcal{K} Class \mathcal{K} functions: continuous, strictly increasing, zero at zero
\mathcal{K}_\infty Class \mathcal{K} functions that are unbounded
\mathcal{KL} Class \mathcal{KL} functions: \beta(s,t) is \mathcal{K} in s and decreasing to zero in t
\mathcal{L}_2 Square-integrable signals: \int_0^\infty \|x(t)\|^2 dt < \infty
\mathcal{L}_\infty Essentially bounded signals: \sup_t \|x(t)\| < \infty
\nabla Gradient operator
\partial Partial derivative
\mathbf{1}_n Vector of ones of length n
I_n n\times n identity matrix

A.2 Input‑to‑State Stability (ISS)

Definition A.1 (ISS).
The system \dot{x} = f(x, u), with state x \in \mathbb{R}^n and input u(t) \in \mathbb{R}^m, is input‑to‑state stable if there exist \beta \in \mathcal{KL} and \gamma \in \mathcal{K}_\infty such that for every initial condition x(0) and every bounded input u(\cdot),

\|x(t)\| \le \beta(\|x(0)\|, t) + \gamma\left(\sup_{0\le \tau \le t} \|u(\tau)\|\right), \quad \forall t\ge 0.

Lemma A.1 (ISS Lyapunov Function).
If there exists a smooth function V:\mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} and \alpha_1, \alpha_2, \alpha_3, \sigma \in \mathcal{K}_\infty such that

\alpha_1(\|x\|) \le V(x) \le \alpha_2(\|x\|), \qquad \frac{\partial V}{\partial x} f(x,u) \le -\alpha_3(\|x\|) + \sigma(\|u\|),

then the system is ISS.

Lemma A.2 (Small‑Gain Theorem for Interconnected Systems).
Consider a network of N subsystems

\dot{x}_i = f_i(x_i, u_i, d_i), \quad i=1,\dots,N,

where d_i = \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} h_{ij}(x_j). Suppose each subsystem is ISS with respect to d_i with gain functions \gamma_{ij} such that

\|x_i(t)\| \le \beta_i(\|x_i(0)\|, t) + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \gamma_{ij}(\|x_j\|_\infty) + \gamma_{iw}(\|w\|_\infty).

If the matrix \Gamma = [\gamma_{ij}] satisfies \rho(\Gamma) < 1 (spectral radius), then the whole network is ISS with respect to the external disturbances w.

Proof. See [Jiang et al., 1996; Dashkovskiy et al., 2007].

A.3 Finite‑Time Stability

Definition A.2 (Finite‑Time Stability).
The origin of \dot{x} = f(x) is finite‑time stable if it is Lyapunov stable and there exists a settling‑time function T(x_0) < \infty such that for every initial condition x_0, the solution satisfies x(t) = 0 for all t \ge T(x_0).

Lemma A.3 (Finite‑Time Convergence).
If there exists a Lyapunov function V and constants \alpha > 0, \beta \in (0,1) such that

\dot{V}(x) \le -\alpha V(x)^\beta,

then the origin is finite‑time stable with settling time

T(x_0) \le \frac{V(x_0)^{1-\beta}}{\alpha(1-\beta)}.

Proof. See [Bhat & Bernstein, 2000].

A.4 Graph Theory

Let \mathcal{G} = (\mathcal{V}, \mathcal{E}) be an undirected graph with |\mathcal{V}| = N. The adjacency matrix A has entries a_{ij} = 1 if (i,j)\in\mathcal{E}, else 0. The degree matrix D = \operatorname{diag}(d_i) with d_i = \sum_j a_{ij}. The graph Laplacian is L = D - A. It is positive semidefinite, with eigenvalues 0 = \lambda_1 \le \lambda_2 \le \cdots \le \lambda_N. The second smallest eigenvalue \lambda_2 is the algebraic connectivity.

A.5 Convex Optimization and ADMM

The Alternating Direction Method of Multipliers (ADMM) solves problems of the form

\min_{x,z} f(x) + g(z) \quad \text{s.t.} \quad Ax + Bz = c.

The augmented Lagrangian is

\mathcal{L}_\rho(x,z,\lambda) = f(x) + g(z) + \lambda^\top(Ax+Bz-c) + \frac{\rho}{2}\|Ax+Bz-c\|^2.

The ADMM iterations are:

\begin{aligned}
x^{k+1} &= \arg\min_x \mathcal{L}_\rho(x, z^k, \lambda^k), \\
z^{k+1} &= \arg\min_z \mathcal{L}_\rho(x^{k+1}, z, \lambda^k), \\
\lambda^{k+1} &= \lambda^k + \rho (Ax^{k+1} + Bz^{k+1} - c).
\end{aligned}

Under convexity and certain conditions, ADMM converges to the optimal solution with rate O(1/k). With Nesterov acceleration, the rate improves to O(1/k^2) for strongly convex objectives.

