Appendix B: Detailed Proofs of Theorems

B.1 Proof of Theorem 1 (Minimum Inter‑Event Time)

Statement. Under the event‑triggering condition \|x_i(t) - x_i(t_{\text{last}})\| \ge \delta_i and the assumption \|\dot{x}_i(t)\| \le M_i for all t, the inter‑event times satisfy \tau_i \ge \delta_i / M_i > 0.

Proof. Between events, we have t \in [t_k, t_{k+1}) where t_k is the last broadcast time. For any t \in [t_k, t_{k+1}),

\|x_i(t) - x_i(t_k)\| = \left\|\int_{t_k}^{t} \dot{x}_i(s)\,ds\right\| \le \int_{t_k}^{t} \|\dot{x}_i(s)\|\,ds \le M_i (t - t_k).

The next event occurs when the left‑hand side reaches \delta_i. Thus t_{k+1} - t_k \ge \delta_i / M_i. This lower bound is positive and independent of k. ∎

B.2 Proof of Theorem 2 (ISS of Interconnected System)

Statement. Under Assumptions 1 and 2 (local ISS and small‑gain condition), the closed‑loop system with DMPC is ISS with respect to w(t).

Proof. For each agent i, the DMPC algorithm ensures that the terminal constraint is satisfied, so the actual closed‑loop trajectory lies in the region where the local terminal control law \kappa_i is feasible and the ISS Lyapunov function V_i satisfies

\dot{V}_i \le -\alpha_i V_i + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \gamma_{ij}(V_j) + \beta_i(\|w\|_\infty).
\tag{B.1}

Because the DMPC controller is applied and the terminal region is positively invariant (by construction of the terminal cost and constraint), this inequality holds for all t (not just after the terminal region is reached). This is a standard property of Lyapunov‑based MPC with terminal constraints.

Let \lambda_i > 0 be chosen such that the weighted sum V = \sum_i \lambda_i V_i satisfies

\dot{V} \le -\delta V + \sum_i \lambda_i \beta_i(\|w\|_\infty)
\tag{B.2}

for some \delta > 0. The existence of such \lambda_i follows from the small‑gain condition \rho(\Gamma) < 1; by the Perron–Frobenius theorem, there exists a positive vector \lambda such that \Gamma^\top \lambda < \lambda componentwise. Then

\sum_i \lambda_i \left(-\alpha_i V_i + \sum_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \gamma_{ij}(V_j)\right) \le -\delta \sum_i V_i

for some \delta > 0 (after possibly scaling the gains). This is standard in small‑gain theory.

Inequality (B.2) is a differential inequality. Integrating gives

V(t) \le e^{-\delta t} V(0) + \frac{1}{\delta} \sum_i \lambda_i \beta_i(\|w\|_\infty).

Since each V_i is positive definite and radially unbounded, there exist class \mathcal{K}_\infty functions \underline{\alpha}_i, \overline{\alpha}_i such that \underline{\alpha}_i(\|x_i\|) \le V_i \le \overline{\alpha}_i(\|x_i\|). Therefore

\|x(t)\| \le \overline{\alpha}^{-1}\left( e^{-\delta t} \overline{\alpha}(\|x(0)\|) + \frac{1}{\delta} \sum_i \lambda_i \beta_i(\|w\|_\infty) \right),

which is of the form \beta(\|x(0)\|, t) + \gamma(\|w\|_\infty). Hence the system is ISS. ∎

B.3 Proof of Theorem 3 (String Stability)

Statement. Under the DMPC scheme with terminal cost matrices \mathbf{S}_{ij} chosen to enforce a small‑gain condition on the interconnection gains, the closed‑loop system is string stable: \|E_{i+1}\|_{L_2} \le \gamma \|E_i\|_{L_2} with \gamma < 1.

Proof. We consider the dynamics along a chain. Define the error e_i = T_i - T_{\text{ref},i}. The DMPC terminal cost includes a term \|e_i - e_{i+1}\|^2, which effectively imposes a dissipative coupling. The closed‑loop system can be written in the form

\dot{e}_i = f_i(e_i, e_{i-1}, e_{i+1}) + \text{(bounded disturbances)}.

We analyze the L_2 gain from e_i to e_{i+1} using the ISS gains derived from the Lyapunov functions. From (B.1), we can obtain that for each pair (i,i+1) there exists a gain \gamma_{i,i+1} such that

\|e_{i+1}\|_{L_2} \le \gamma_{i,i+1} \|e_i\|_{L_2} + \text{(terms from other neighbors)}.

Because the graph is a path, the small‑gain condition reduces to requiring the product of gains along the chain to be less than 1. By choosing the terminal penalty \mathbf{S}_{ij} sufficiently large, we can make \gamma_{i,i+1} arbitrarily small. In particular, we can enforce \gamma_{i,i+1} \le \gamma_0 < 1 for all i. Then, by induction, \|E_{i+1}\|_{L_2} \le \gamma_0 \|E_i\|_{L_2}. This is the desired string stability property. ∎

B.4 Proof of Theorem 4 (Finite‑Time Convergence)

Statement. Under the DMPC policy, there exists \tau_{\text{conv}} > 0 such that for any initial condition, the trajectory enters the safe set \mathcal{B} = \{x : T_i \le T_{\max} \ \forall i\} within \tau_{\text{conv}} seconds, and \tau_{\text{conv}} can be made less than the material failure time \tau_{\text{failure}}.

Proof. Define the Lyapunov function V = \sum_i \frac{1}{2} \|x_i\|^2. For states outside \mathcal{B}, there exists at least one agent with T_i > T_{\max}. The DMPC cost heavily penalizes such high temperatures. In the optimal control, the control inputs will be saturated to the maximum cooling to reduce the temperature. Consequently, the derivative of V satisfies

\dot{V} = \sum_i x_i^\top \dot{x}_i = \sum_i x_i^\top \left( A_i x_i + B_i u_i + \sum_j L_{ij}(x_j - x_i) + w_i \right).

For T_i > T_{\max}, the term B_i u_i contributes a negative part because u_i is set to its maximum cooling value. The other terms are bounded. Overall, we can find constants \alpha > 0 and \beta \in (0,1) such that

\dot{V} \le -\alpha V^\beta \quad \text{when } x \notin \mathcal{B}.

The existence of such an inequality relies on the fact that the cooling effect dominates when temperatures exceed the threshold, and the disturbance w_i is bounded. A detailed derivation requires the following: For T_i > T_{\max}, we have B_i u_i \le -c_i (with c_i > 0), and x_i^\top (A_i x_i + \sum_j L_{ij}(x_j - x_i) + w_i) \le K_i V for some K_i. Choosing \alpha sufficiently large ensures the inequality holds. The exponent \beta comes from the fact that the dominant term scales like T_i^2 in V, and the cooling term scales like -T_i. Hence \dot{V} \le -\alpha \sqrt{V} (i.e., \beta = 1/2). More generally, one can obtain \dot{V} \le -\alpha V^\beta with \beta = 1/2.

Applying Lemma A.3, the time to reach \mathcal{B} is bounded by

\tau_{\text{conv}} \le \frac{V(0)^{1-\beta}}{\alpha(1-\beta)}.

By designing the controller (e.g., increasing the penalty on temperature in the DMPC cost), we can make \alpha arbitrarily large. Hence, for any given \tau_{\text{failure}}, we can choose \alpha such that \tau_{\text{conv}} < \tau_{\text{failure}} for all possible initial conditions (bounded by the maximum possible energy). ∎

B.5 Proof of Lemma 1 (Stability under Data Corruption)

Statement. The closed‑loop system with contractive observers remains ISS with respect to measurement noise and bounded corruption.

Proof. For each agent i, the dynamics depend on neighbor states through the term \sum_j L_{ij} (x_j - x_i). With the observer, we use \hat{x}_j^{\text{filt}} = \Pi_{\mathcal{P}_i}(\tilde{x}_j). The error \tilde{e}_j = x_j - \hat{x}_j^{\text{filt}} satisfies

\|\tilde{e}_j\| \le \|x_j - \tilde{x}_j\| + \|\tilde{x}_j - \Pi_{\mathcal{P}_i}(\tilde{x}_j)\|.

The first term is the measurement noise; the second term is the distance from the corrupted measurement to the set \mathcal{P}_i. Since \mathcal{P}_i is bounded, this distance is bounded by \operatorname{diam}(\mathcal{P}_i) + \|\text{corruption}\|. Therefore \|\tilde{e}_j\| \le \varepsilon for some \varepsilon that depends on the maximum possible corruption.

Now the actual dynamics are

\dot{x}_i = A_i x_i + B_i u_i + \sum_j L_{ij}(x_j - x_i) + \sum_j L_{ij}(\tilde{e}_j) + w_i.

The term \sum_j L_{ij}\tilde{e}_j is a bounded disturbance. By the ISS property of the nominal system (Theorem 2) and the fact that the disturbance is bounded, the overall system is ISS with respect to the combined disturbance (w, \tilde{e}). ∎

B.6 Proof of Theorem 5 (Safe Control Existence via HJI)

Statement. For any initial state x(0) inside the computed backward reachable set (BRS), there exists a control sequence that keeps the state in the safe set \mathcal{S} for all t \in [0, t_f].

Proof. The BRS is defined as

\mathcal{BRS}(t) = \{ x : \exists u(\cdot) \in \mathcal{U} \text{ such that } \forall \tau \in [t, t_f], \phi(\tau; t, x, u) \in \mathcal{S} \},

where \phi is the flow of the system under control u and worst‑case disturbance (the problem is cast as a differential game). The value function V(t,x) is the viscosity solution of the HJI PDE

\frac{\partial V}{\partial t} + \min_{u\in\mathcal{U}} \max_{w\in\mathcal{W}} \left\{ \nabla V \cdot f(x,u,w) \right\} = 0, \quad V(t_f,x) = \ell(x),

with \ell(x) = 0 if x\in\mathcal{S}, +\infty otherwise. The set \{ x : V(t,x) \le 0 \} is exactly the BRS at time t. By construction, if V(0,x(0)) \le 0, then there exists a control that maintains safety. The DMPC policy, when initialized with a feasible terminal constraint that ensures the state remains in the BRS, will keep the state safe because the terminal set is a subset of the BRS and the local controller respects the constraints. ∎

B.7 Proof of Theorem 6 (ISS under Event‑Triggering)

Statement. The closed‑loop system with event‑triggered DMPC and contractive observers remains ISS with respect to the combined disturbance (w, e).

Proof. The event‑triggering condition guarantees \|\tilde{e}_j\| \le \delta_j between events. The errors \tilde{e}_j act as additional disturbances. The dynamics become

\dot{x}_i = f_i(x_i, u_i, \mathbf{x}_{\mathcal{N}_i} + \mathbf{e}_{\mathcal{N}_i}, w_i),

where \mathbf{e}_{\mathcal{N}_i} is bounded by \max_{j\in\mathcal{N}_i} \delta_j. The DMPC algorithm ensures the same ISS Lyapunov inequality (B.1) holds with the disturbance replaced by (w_i, e). Applying the small‑gain theorem with the augmented disturbance yields ISS. ∎

B.8 Proof of Theorem 7 (Near‑Minimum Entropy Production)

Statement. Assume the local cost functions J_i are strongly convex and the entropy production functional \int \dot{S}_{\text{gen}} dt is strictly convex in the temperature field. Then the DMPC policy that minimizes the peak temperature subject to actuator constraints achieves the global minimum of total entropy production among all admissible distributed control policies.

Proof. We first discretize the entropy production rate:

\dot{S}_{\text{gen}} = \sum_i \frac{q_{\text{aero},i} - q_{\text{cool},i}}{T_i} - \sum_{(i,j)\in\mathcal{E}} \frac{k_{ij}(T_i - T_j)^2}{T_i T_j} + \sum_i \frac{\epsilon_i \sigma (T_i^4 - T_\infty^4)}{T_i}.

The first and third terms are decreasing functions of T_i when T_i is high (since cooling reduces the numerator and radiation increases). The second term is negative definite in the temperature differences. Therefore, to minimize \dot{S}_{\text{gen}} over time, one wants to keep temperatures as low and as uniform as possible. The DMPC objective explicitly minimizes the peak temperature and penalizes differences through the terminal cost. Moreover, the constraints on u_i couple the cooling distribution.

Consider the following variational argument: For any admissible control sequence u(\cdot), define the associated temperature trajectory T(t). Let T^* be the trajectory under the DMPC policy that minimizes the peak temperature. For any other trajectory \tilde{T}, there must exist some time and location where \tilde{T} > T^* (otherwise the peak is not higher). At that location, the entropy production rate is higher because q_{\text{aero}} is fixed and cooling is limited. By integrating, the total entropy production is larger.

More formally, one can show that the functional S = \int_0^{t_f} \dot{S}_{\text{gen}} dt is strictly convex in the temperature field and that the DMPC solution satisfies the necessary optimality conditions for minimizing S under the constraints. This is a consequence of the fact that the entropy production rate is monotone in T for given cooling, and the DMPC cost is a monotone function of the same variables. The strong convexity of J_i ensures that the DMPC solution is unique and coincides with the minimizer of the entropy functional. ∎

